A hitting set is a set of squares that intersects every possible 2x1 rectangle (either horizontal or vertical) on the grid. 1. **Understanding the Grid and Rectangles**: - The 3x3 grid has 9 squares. - A 2x1 rectangle can cover two adjacent squares either horizontally or vertically. - There are 12 possible positions for the rectangle: 6 horizontal and 6 vertical. 2. **Hitting Set Concept**: - A hitting set is a set of squares such that every possible rectangle covers at least one square in the set. - The goal is to find the smallest hitting set, which translates to the minimum number of guesses needed to ensure covering at least one square of any hidden rectangle. 3. **Analyzing Possible Hitting Sets**: - After considering various combinations of squares, it was determined that a hitting set of size 4 is sufficient. - The set {E, D, F, H} was found to cover all 12 possible rectangles: - **E** covers: A-B, B-C, D-E, E-F, G-H, H-I. - **D** covers: A-D, D-G. - **F** covers: C-F, F-I. - **H** covers: G-H, H-I. - This set covers all 12 rectangles, ensuring that any hidden rectangle will have at least one square guessed. 4. **Verification**: - If the hidden rectangle is placed in any position, at least one of the guessed squares (E, D, F, H) will be covered. - For example, if the hidden rectangle is B-E or E-H, the square E is guessed, ensuring coverage. Thus, the minimum number of guesses required to ensure finding at least one covered square is \(\boxed{4}\).
